    "# Task 3: CNN Model Development\n",
    "\n",
    "### CNN Architecture Design\n",
    "\n",
    "The CNN model was designed carefully to work well with a small dataset and avoid overfitting.\n",
    "First, the model uses three convolutional blocks. These layers help the model learn features step by step. The early layers detect simple patterns like edges and textures, while deeper layers learn more complex shapes and specific gesture patterns.\n",
    "Batch Normalization is added after each convolution layer to make training more stable. It keeps the values in a good range, which helps the model learn faster and more smoothly.\n",
    "Max Pooling is used to reduce the size of the feature maps. This makes the model faster and helps it focus on the most important features, even if the object position changes slightly.\n",
    "Spatial Dropout is used to prevent overfitting. Instead of dropping random pixels, it removes entire feature maps, making the model less dependent on specific features.\n",
    "Then instead of using a Flatten layer, the model uses Global Average Pooling. This reduces the number of parameters, which is very helpful for small datasets and lowers the risk of overfitting.\n",
    "The Dense layers with L2 regularization help control the size of the weights. This prevents the model from becoming too complex and overfitting the data.\n",
    "The model uses ReLU activation because it helps the model learn non-linear patterns and avoids problems like vanishing gradients.\n",
    "Finally, the Softmax layer is used at the output to give probabilities for each of the three classes, so the model can decide which class is most likely.\n",
    "\n",
    "Training Decisions:\n",
    "\n",
    "- To improve training, Early Stopping is used. It monitors the validation loss and stops training if there is no improvement after some time. This helps prevent overfitting.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The learning rate is set to 0.001 using the Adam optimizer, which is a good default value and works well for small datasets."
   ]
