  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "764e5df5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transfer learning is a powerful technique in deep learning where a model that has already been trained is reused and adapted for a new task. Instead of building a model from scratch, transfer learning allows us to take advantage of the knowledge the model has already gained.\n",
    "The reason this approach works so well is because the pretrained model has already learned to identify general visual features such as edges, textures, and shapes. These features are common across most image-related tasks, including hand gesture recognition. By freezing the earlier layers of the model, their learned weights remain unchanged, preserving this valuable knowledge. Only the final layers of the network are retrained using the smaller, task-specific dataset, allowing the model to adapt to the new classification problem.\n",
    "This method is especially useful when working with small datasets. Training a deep convolutional neural network from scratch typically requires a large amount of data to perform well. With a limited number of images, a custom model is more likely to overfitting, meaning it memorizes the training data instead of learning patterns that generalize. In contrast, a pretrained model already has strong feature extraction capabilities, which helps improve performance even when the available data is limited.\n",
    "During training, Early Stopping is applied to monitor the validation loss and prevent overfitting. Since pretrained models tend to converge faster than models trained from scratch, a smaller patience value = 5 is used. This is to ensures that training stops once the model’s performance stops improving, resulting in a more efficient and reliable training process."
